05847nam a22008175i 9780674067639DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132012mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013943738  a97806740676397 a10.4159/harvard.97806740676392doi  a(DE-B1597)178054  a(OCoLC)979742837  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aKZ1252 7aLAW0510002bisacsh04a341/.11 aPosner, Eric A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEconomic Foundations of International Law /cA. O Sykes, Eric A. Posner. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2013] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (374 p.) :b2 line illustrations, 4 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tI Basics -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Fundamentals of International Law -- t3. Economic Analysis of International Law— the Essentials -- tII General Aspects of International Law -- t4. Sovereignty and Attributes of Statehood -- t5. Customary International Law -- t6. Treaties -- t7. International Institutions -- t8. State Responsibility -- t9. Remedies -- t10. The Intersection between International Law and Domestic Law -- tIII Traditional Public International Law -- t11. Treatment of Aliens, Foreign Property, and Foreign Debt -- t12. The Use of Force -- t13. The Conduct of War -- t14. Human Rights -- t15. International Criminal Law -- tIV The Environment -- t16. International Environmental Law -- t17. The Law of the Sea -- tV International Economic Law -- t18. International Trade -- t19. International Investment, Antitrust, and Monetary Law -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a  aThe ever-increasing exchange of goods and ideas among nations, as well as cross-border pollution, global warming, and international crime, pose urgent questions for international law. Here, two respected scholars provide an intellectual framework for assessing these pressing legal problems from a rational choice perspective. The approach assumes that states are rational, forward-looking agents which use international law to address the actions of other states that may have consequences for their own citizens, and to obtain the benefits of international cooperation. It further assumes that in the absence of a central enforcement agency—that is, a world government—international law must be self-enforcing. States must believe that if they violate international agreements, other states will retaliate. Consequently, Eric A. Posner and Alan O. Sykes devote considerable attention to the challenges of enforcing international law, which begin with the difficulties of determining what it is. In the absence of an international constitution, the sources for international law are vague. Lawyers must rely on statements contained in all manner of official documents and on simple observation of states’ behavior. This looseness leads international institutions such as the United Nations to deliver conflicting interpretations of the law’s most basic principles. The authors describe the conditions under which international law succeeds or fails, across a wide range of issues, including war crimes, human rights, international criminal law, principles of state responsibility, law of the sea, international trade regulation, and international investment law.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aLAW / International.2bisacsh1 aSykes, A. O, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2013z9783110317350oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE LAW  2013z978311031720608iTitle is part of